data.name: txtDSVertAccReport.HelpString
data.value: What sort of quantitative or qualitative tests were performed to assess the vertical positional accuracy of the features within the data set? A good data set requires some amount of QA/QC; provide details of any steps taken to ensure a quality data product. This is a required element so if no tests were performed, simply state: "A formal accuracy assessment of the vertical positional information in the data set has either not been conducted, or is not applicable."

data.name: txtDSHorizAccReport.HelpString
data.value: What sort of quantitative or qualitative tests were performed to assess the horizontal positional accuracy of the features within the data set? Were features ground-truthed with GPS? Were features verified in high resolution imagery (if so, list the details in 'Source Info')? Provide as much information as possible. A good data set requires some amount of QA/QC; provide details of any steps taken to ensure a quality data product. This is a required element so if no tests were performed, simply state: "A formal accuracy assessment of the horizontal positional information in the data set has not been conducted."

data.name: txtProcessStep1.HelpString
data.value: Every data set must have at least one processing step. An acceptable default value could be: "Development of the data set by the agency / individuals identified in the 'Originator' element in the Identification Info section of the record." A more detailed and complete lineage section for a GIS data set might have 4 processing steps: 1. Digitization of source inputs (describe). 2. Merging of secondary data set (describe). 3. Projection into final CRS (describe). 4. Quality assurance and Quality Control ('QAQC') process (describe).

data.name: txtSource1ScaleDenom.HelpString
data.value: Provide the denominator of the source scale. For instance, most USGS topo maps are at the 1:24,000 scale. In another example, if the source data was digitized, at what scale did digitizers capture the features on screen?

data.name: txtSource1Abbreviation.HelpString
data.value: An abbreviation for the data source is required by the FGDC standard. This is just a short name that might be used to refer to the data set. For instance, "National Hydrography Dataset - Flowlines" could be abbreviated with "NHD Flow".

data.name: cboSource1CurrentnessRef.HelpString
data.value: Provide additional detail about the time period of the information in the source data set. How current is the source data set? ["Ground Condition": time period date(s) and the information in the data set reflect when a site was physically visited. This category may only be appropriate for certain data types.] ["Observed": time period date(s) and the information in the data set reflect conditions at a particular time of data capture. Physical presence not required; information may have been collected by an instrument or tool.] ["Publication": Additional information about how the data were captured is unavailable. Time period date(s) represent the publication date of the inputs used to produce the data set.]

data.name: txtSource1BeginDate.HelpString
data.value: Enter the earliest date of any information represented in the data. If the month and day are not known, simply enter the year (in the YYYY format). If all the data represent information from a single point in time, enter the same value in both the 'Beginning Date' and 'End Date' fields.

data.name: txtSource1EndDate.HelpString
data.value: Enter the most recent date of any information represented in the data. If the month and day are not known, simply enter the year (in the YYYY format). If all the data represent information from a single point in time, enter the same value in both the 'Beginning Date' and 'End Date' fields.

data.name: txtSource1PubDate.ToolTip
data.value: Provide the date of publication. If a traditional 'publication date' is unknown, provide the date when the data set was finalized and / or made available. If month and day are not known, simply enter the year (in the YYYY format).

data.name: txtDSCompletenessReport.HelpString
data.value: Provide details on what is captured in the data set in relation to all real world occurrences of the phenomenon. For example, if the data represents a tree survey, are ALL trees included or only those of a certain size or species? Given the limitations of how the data were produced, how complete can the user expect the data to be? Provide as much information as possible. This is a required element so if no tests were performed, simply state: "Data set is considered complete for the information presented, as described in the abstract. Users are advised to read the rest of the metadata record carefully for additional details."

data.name: Label167.Text
data.value: Does the data set represent only certain types or instances of a phenomenon? Do the data represent occurrences only within a fixed geographic area? Provide information about what is included in the data set versus what is not. See help for more info.

data.name: txtDSLogicalAccuracy.HelpString
data.value: What checks have you performed to ensure that the data set matches up with the description provided in the abstract and purpose? Have you verified that features and data entries are not duplicated? Do all values fall in a valid range (for example, a data set of precipitation values should not have negative values)? Provide as much information as possible. A good data set requires some amount of QA/QC; provide details of any steps taken to ensure a quality data product. This is a required element so if no tests were performed, simply state: "No formal logical accuracy tests were conducted."

data.name: Label165.Text
data.value: Does the actual data match up with the details you have provided about it? Do all values fall within expected ranges? Have you checked for data duplication/omission? Were topology tests conducted to ensure the integrity of geospatial data? See help for more info.

data.name: txtDSAttributeAccuracy.HelpString
data.value: How accurate are the presented data values, relative to the real world? Were values verified through ground truthing or comparison to another data set of higher accuracy? If any tests were performed, please include the results. Provide as much information as possible. A good data set requires some amount of QA/QC; provide details of any steps taken to ensure a quality data product. This is a required element so if no tests were performed, simply state: "No formal attribute accuracy tests were conducted."

data.name: Label163.Text
data.value: How accurate are the values in the data set relative to "true" values? Were any tests performed to assess the accuracy of values? Please describe any methods used to ensure quality / accuracy in the data. See help for more info.

data.name: Panel4.HelpString
data.value: Provide details on on what is captured in the data set in relation to all real world occurrences of the phenomenon. For example, if the data represents a tree survey are ALL trees included or only those of a certain size or species? Given the limitations of the data were produced, how complete can the user expect the data to be? Provide as much information as possible.

data.name: txtDSDistFees.HelpString
data.value: List any fees associated with acquiring the data. This tool requires this element, so if no fees are associated with data acquisition, use the default value of: "None. No fees are applicable for obtaining the data set."

data.name: txtDSDistLiability.HelpString
data.value: If there are any explicit distribution disclaimers or liability limitations, list them here. This is a required element, so a good default value for this field (if no specific terms are otherwise outlined) is: "Distributor assumes no liability for misuse of data. Please read the metadata record carefully to understand the data set."

data.name: Label91.Text
data.value:
Does your record contain a taxonomic classification? This is a key indicator that a record is in the "Biological Data Profile" (BDP) standard. If your record has a taxonomy section, select the BDP and 'FGDC-STD-001.1-1999' options above.
Although the taxonomy section is not visible in this tool, this section will remain unchanged and will be present in the output record.

data.name: cboMetaStandardName.HelpString
data.value: When used properly, this tool generates metadata compliant with Federal Geographic Data Committee (FGDC) standards, specifically the 'Content Standard for Digital Geospatial Metadata' (CSDGM). This tool collects the core information needed for a basic CSDGM record, although it will also honor any metadata content in an input record that is part of the Biological Data Profile (BDP) extension of the CSDGM. Users will not be able to edit this content using this tool (for example: taxonomic information, analytical tools, formal methodologies, etc.) but the tool will not remove it. Most users should select "FGDC Content Standard for Digital Geospatial Metadata" from the drop-down menu for this element. If your record had a different metadata standard name specified however, that value will be retained in this field. If your record has other BDP elements, or if you will add them using an external process you should select "FGDC Biological Data Profile of the Content Standard for Digital Geospatial Metadata" for this element.

data.name: cboMetaStandardVersion.HelpString
data.value: Please see the help info for the 'Metadata Standard Name' element above. If your record is in the basic FGDC-CSDGM format (most will be), the "FGDC-STD-001-1998" should be selected for this element. If your record contains elements from the Biological Data Profile (BDP) extension of the CSDGM, you should select "FGDC-STD-001.1-1999" from the drop-down menu.

data.name: txtDSLargerWorkSeriesName.HelpString
data.value: What is the name of the data series that the LARGER WORK is part of? This might be "USGS Data Series", if applicable. Alternatively, this could be the name of a publication or journal, or an online series in which the larger work is an installment.

data.name: txtDSLargerWorkSeriesNum.HelpString
data.value: What is the unique number or name that identifies this LARGER WORK within the series? This might correspond to a USGS 'Data Series' number, or the specific volume/edition of a peer-reviewed journal, etc.

data.name: txtDSLargerWorkPubDate.HelpString
data.value: Provide the date of publication. If a traditional 'publication date' is unknown, provide the date when the data set was finalized and / or made available. If month and day are not known, simply enter the year (in the YYYY format).

data.name: txtDSTimePeriodSingleDate.HelpString
data.value: If the data represent information captured or recorded at one point in time, enter the date using the single date option. If the month and day are not known, simply enter the year (in the YYYY format).

data.name: dgvDSTimePeriodMultiDate.HelpString
data.value: If the data represent information captured or recorded at various points through time, enter the individual dates here. This option should be used when the date range option is not appropriate – e.g., when data represent a disparate collection of measurements or when temporal currency of the data set can be linked to multiple distinct points in time. If the month and day are not known, simply enter the year (in the YYYY format).

data.name: cboDSTimePeriodCurrentRef.HelpString
data.value: Provide additional detail about the time period of the information in the data set. How current is the data set? ["Ground Condition" = time period date(s) and the information in the data set reflect when a site was physically visited. This category may only be appropriate for certain data types.] ["Observed" = time period date(s) and the information in the data set reflect conditions at a particular time of data capture. Physical presence not required; information may have been collected by an instrument or tool.] ["Publication" = Additional information about how the data were captured is unavailable. Time period date(s) represent the publication date of the inputs used to produce the data set.]

data.name: txtDSPubDate.HelpString
data.value: Provide the date of publication. If a traditional 'publication date' is unknown, provide the date when the data set was finalized and / or made available. If month and day are not known, simply enter the year (in the YYYY format).

data.name: txtDSAbstract.HelpString
data.value: The Abstract should contain details about the data such that future users clearly understand what is being represented. Including information about the larger projects out of which the data sets were produced is often useful.

data.name: txtDSAccessCon.HelpString
data.value: Provide details about any limitations regarding who can access the data set, if applicable. In some cases, restrictions on USE may differ from restrictions on ACCESS.For instance, a data set may only be available for download on a university's server, but available for use by anyone. (Limited access, but not use). Alternatively, a data set may be freely available but only usable by individuals with a particular type of software (Limited use, but not access).

data.name: Label89.Text
data.value: Describe any restrictions or legal prerequisites for ACCESSING the data set. Access Constraints may include restrictions applied to assure the protection of privacy or intellectual property, and any special restrictions or limitations to accessing the data set.

data.name: Label90.Text
data.value: Describe any restrictions or legal prerequisites for USING the data set. Use Constraints may include restrictions applied to assure the protection of privacy or intellectual property, and any special restrictions or limitations on using the data set.

data.name: txtDSUseCon.HelpString
data.value: Provide details about any limitations regarding who can use the data set, if applicable. In some cases, restrictions on USE may differ from restrictions on ACCESS.For instance, a data set may only be available for download on a university's server, but available for use by anyone. (Limited access, but not use). Alternatively, a data set may be freely available but only usable by individuals with a particular type of software (Limited use, but not access).

data.name: cboDSDataStatus.HelpString
data.value: Describe the status of the data set. ["Complete": The data set is finalized and represents a finished product.] ["In Work" : The data set is not finalized and work on the data set is ongoing.] ["Planned" : The data set does not exist but its production is planned. The metadata record outlines the overall goals of the project at this point and will be updated as the data is created.]

data.name: txtDSSeriesName.HelpString
data.value: What is the name of the data series that the data set is part of? This might be "USGS Data Series", if applicable. Alternatively, this could be the name of a publication or journal, or an online series in which the data set is an installment.

data.name: Label87.Text
data.value: Metadata Parser (MP) is a utility for checking the compliance of an FGDC-CSDGM metadata record against the FGDC's official standard. The output provided below will identify any errors in a record, and will provide the location in the XML file where the error is located. This location is listed as the 'xpath.' While this tool attempts to populate (or provide the means to populate) all the necessary fields, some errors may require that a record be opened in external software for final editing.
